-  Scheve & Stasavage 2006: sostienen que la religión puede tener un efecto negativo en las preferencias, dado que modera el riesgo en la medida que contrubuye a bienestar inmaterial (e.g. compañía y consuelo) o material (e.g. ofrecer trabajo, prestar dinero). Decrese la demanda por **insurance**.  

# Mobility

* Prospective upward mobility (POUM) [@benabou_social_2001;@Fong2004;@Jaime-Castillo2008]

* Social Mobility (SM) [@jaime-castillo_social_2019;@valdimarsdottir_social_2022;@alesina_intergenerational_2018]

Education can be considered as proxy for mobility prospects. 
Educational mobility does not have an effect. However, occupational mobility does it. [@alesina_preferences_2010]

How previous research intended to capture the influence of prospects about future income relies mainly on subjective expectations about future abstract status position [@Alesina2005]. In this regard, @rueda_who_2019 discuss this approach because it only considers short periods in time, not the complete life cycle.  

future_income = age + age2 + education + age*education + e

They assume that individuals have some knowledge about life-cycle income profile of people with the same level of education [@rueda_who_2019, p. 41]

- expectations of income are not related to risk aversion
- an individual demands more redistribution today, for example, if she knows she will be poorer in the future

- correlation of future income is low (0.2 to 0.3) with actual income.
- estimaron el ingreso futuro usando ols

Ideas:
- cuánto crees que esta persona gana
- cuánto crees que esta persona va ganar en X años
- cuánto crees que esta persona debería ganar

@rueda_who_2019 "the importance of present income as a determinant of redistribution preferences is highly variable, both cross-nationally and temporally."

lifetime income model based on labour economics that considers education and experience as key drivers of income, therefore, preferences for redistribution. The key concepts here are social insurance, risk and mobility [@rueda_who_2019]

The prospective social mobility model assumes that the tax revenues are fixed for both, origin and destination [@alesina_preferences_2010]

